# CLI Workflow Reference

## Extract

```bash
bun cli/extract.ts --reader <name> --url <url> [--out ./output] [--headed] [--profile <dir>]
```

Available readers: `takecomic`, `nico-douga`, `comic-walker`, `speed-binb`, `kindle`, `comicbushi`, `comic-pixiv`

### Options
- `--reader` / `-r`: Reader name (required)
- `--url` / `-u`: URL to extract from (required)
- `--out` / `-o`: Output directory (default: `./output`)
- `--headed`: Show browser window (useful for debugging)
- `--profile`: Chrome user data directory (for sites that need login)

### Examples
```bash
# Takecomic extraction
bun cli/extract.ts --reader takecomic --url "https://takecomic.jp/episodes/abc123"

# Speed Binb with visible browser
bun cli/extract.ts --reader speed-binb --url "https://storia.takeshobo.co.jp/..." --headed

# Kindle with saved login session
bun cli/extract.ts --reader kindle --url "https://read.amazon.com/..." --profile ./my-chrome-profile
```

## Verify

```bash
bun cli/verify.ts --input <path>
```

- Accepts a directory of images or a ZIP file
- Checks: page count, file sizes, valid image headers, sequential numbering
- Generates `viewer.html` in the input directory for visual review

### Example
```bash
bun cli/verify.ts --input ./output
```

## Full Loop

```bash
bun run build && bun cli/extract.ts -r takecomic -u "URL" && bun cli/verify.ts -i ./output
```

## Sanity Check with Cursor Browser

After extraction + verification:

1. Open `output/viewer.html` in the Cursor browser to see extracted pages
2. Open the original manga URL in the Cursor browser
3. Compare: same page count? readable content? no artifacts or seams?

This comparison against the live source is the best verification -- it catches both extraction bugs and site changes.

## Architecture Notes

- `extract.ts` dispatches to `puppeteer-runner.ts` which launches a real Chrome browser
- The built handler IIFE script is injected into the page via `page.addScriptTag()`
- This is identical to how the Chrome extension injects handlers via `chrome.scripting.executeScript`
- Downloads are intercepted via Chrome DevTools Protocol (CDP)
- The handler runs in the page context with full DOM + fetch access

